cmCourseInfo.description: This course examines the Second World War in the Asia Pacific region and highlights: (1) how imperialism and colonialism of both the Euro-American and Japanese varieties were central to the War's outbreak, conduct, and “resolution”;  (2) various “local” rather than simply national experiences and memories of the War, including those of marginalized groups in Japan and its colonies, “comfort women,” victims of war atrocities, Asian North Americans, African Americans, and Pacific Islanders.
cmCourseInfo.title: The Asia Pacific War
cmCourseInfo.recommendedPreparation: One or more courses on Japan, China, Korea, or Southeast Asia in any department.

cmCourseInfo.description: This course focuses on the use of neuroimaging techniques in understanding how trauma, disorders, and disease impact neural structure and function. Lectures will focus on local and long-range neural impact of pathology and neuroimaging assessment. Lab work will focus on practical skills including image processing, analyses, and experimental design.
cmCourseInfo.title: Clinical Neuroimaging

Timetable Instructions
This course will be part of HMB pre-enrolment. Eligible program students will receive via email a ballot to rank eligible 400-level courses in order of preference between May 15 and June 20, 2019 with decisions confirmed June 28, 2019. Students who are not pre-enrolled in the course but meet the enrolment controls will be able to waitlist for the course once course enrolment starts. Please note that enrollment for practicums (PRA) will close on January 17, 2019 at 4 PM. To make changes to your PRA sections after this date, please contact hmb.undergrad@utoronto.ca
